topic.title: Queue Registers

field-desc.p: This field allows firmware to control the operational state of the queue group. Modifying the value of this field causes the queues to transition to the specified operational state. A transition does not complete until the new operational state is reflected in the State (STATE) field in the corresponding Message Queue Group Status (MQGSTS) register.
Message Queue group does not support a direct transition from the enabled to disabled state.
Firmware must comprehend the possibility of an autonomous state transition to disabled due to an error.

table.title: MRAMSBESTS - MIF Ram Single Bit Error Status

field-desc.p: Associated with each embedded RAM is a status bit. A status bit is set whenever a single bit error is detected in that RAM. SeeTable TBD for embedded RAM indices.
Bits corresponding to unused indices are hardwired to zero.

table.title: MRAMDBESTS - MIF Ram Double Bit Error Status

field-desc.p: Associated with each embedded RAM is a status bit. A status bit is set whenever a double bit error is detected in that RAM. SeeTable TBD for embedded RAM indices.
Bits corresponding to unused indices are hardwired to zero.

table.title: MRAMECTL - MIF Embedded RAM Error Control

field-desc.p: This field contains the index of the embedded RAM on which the command written to the CMD field is performed. SeeTable TBD for embedded RAM indices.

When a value is written to this field, the corresponding operation is performed on the embedded RAM selected in the INDEX field. Selecting an unimplemented RAM index or command causes a NOP to be executed.

table.title: IMQBAL[63:0] - Inbound Message Queue Base Queue Address Low

field-desc.p: This field contains bits six through 37 of the 40-bit physical base address of the queue.
Since a queue must start on a 64B aligned address, bits zero through five are implicitly zero.
Since a queue must be fully contained in the bottom 256GB of physical memory, bits 38 and 39 are implicitly zero.

table.title: IMQBAH[63:0] - Inbound Message Queue Base Queue Address High

field-desc.p: This field contains bits six through 37 of the 40-bit physical base address of the queue.
Since a queue must start on a 64B aligned address, bits zero through five are implicitly zero.
Since a queue must be fully contained in the bottom 256GB of physical memory, bits 38 and 39 are implicitly zero.
This field specifies the size of the queue in terms of 8B message handles.
Since the minimum size of a queue is two entries, the values zero and one are reserved.
When this bit is set, cascaded message processing is enabled.
In an inbound message queue this field specifies queue priority.
Outbound message queues have no associated priority, so this field is read-only with a value of zero in outbound message queues.

table.title: IMQCDA[63:0] - Inbound Message Queue Cascaded Doorbell Address

field-desc.p: This field specifies bits two through 33 of the cascaded doorbell physical address. Since a doorbell register is Dword aligned, bits zero and one are implicitly zero. Cascaded doorbells must be located in the bottom 16GB of physical memory, so bits 34 through 40 are implicitly zero.
If cascaded message processing is not enabled, then the value of this field is ignored..

table.title: IMQBFC[63:0] - Message Queue Backpressure Flow Control

field-desc.desc-title: Outbound Backpressure Flow Control Queue Select
field-desc.p: Each bit in this field represents an outbound message queue (i. e., bit zero represents outbound message queue zero, bit one represents outbound message queue one, and so on). When a bit in this field is set to one, then the inbound message queue is backpressued when the corresponding outbound queue is full. Multiple bits in this field may be set to one, indicating that the inbound message queue is backpressured when any of the corresponding outbound queues are full. When an outbound messagequeue is not implemented by a functional unit, then the corresponding bit in this field is readonly with a value of zero. This field is read-only with a value of zero in outbound message queues..
